Mr. Podesta:

It has been another strong year for The Broad Superintendents Academy, and =
I'd like to share some of our recent successes with you...


 *   So far, 82% of our 2009 graduates have been hired by urban public scho=
ol districts.


*         27% of our 2010 participants have already been hired by urban pub=
lic school districts - four weeks before they've even finished the training=
 program.


 *   80% of Broad Superintendent Academy graduates who served as superinten=
dents for four years improved student achievement faster than other distric=
ts in their states.


 *   In Delaware, one of only two states to win coveted Race to the Top<htt=
p://www2.ed.gov/news/pressreleases/2010/03/03292010.html> funding, Academy =
graduates lead both the state Department of Education (Secretary of Educati=
on Lillian Lowery) and the largest district in the state (Christina School =
District Superintendent Marcia Lyles).

As you may know, the Academy is the only program in the country that recrui=
ts, trains, and supports superintendent candidates with corporate and non-p=
rofit executive management experience.  Academy participants attend several=
 extended weekend sessions over a 10-month period while continuing full tim=
e work in their current jobs, and then receive placement assistance and ext=
ensive support in their new roles.  Tuition and travel costs are covered.

To recommend a colleague or express personal interest, please contact me by=
 August 6, 2010.  The first step in our application process is submission o=
f a professional resume, and the deadline for that is August 13, 2010.  For=
 more information, you may also visit us at www.broadacademy.org<http://www=
.broadacademy.org>.

Melissa Crow
